title.narrative: USAID/Malawi’s Organized Network of Services for Everyone’s Health (ONSE) activity

description.narrative: (Malawi): USAID's Organized Network of Services for Everyone's Health's (ONSE) activity focuses on maternal, neonatal, and child health; voluntary family planning; malaria; water, sanitation, and hygiene (WASH); and nutrition. ONSE will continue to: 1) scale up effective, equitable, locally adapted, and evidence-based interventions to reach poor, marginalized, and vulnerable people, including youth and adolescents; 2) advance quality of priority health services; 3) deliver evidence-based, voluntary family planning interventions at community and facility levels, including roll-out of Sayana press and provision of long-acting and permanent methods; and, 4) support sustainable access to WASH services and products. ONSE will mainstream COVID-19 prevention and response efforts in the health system to contain and mitigate the outbreak while ensuring there are no disruptions of other essential services. ONSE will also strengthen the supervision and management of health facilities and support health governance and accountability by establishing links between civil society, quality improvement activities, and use of data for decision-making. Community mobilization efforts include social and behavior change communication on voluntary family planning, gender norms, timely care seeking, and healthy household practices and behaviors. ONSE contributes to the Integrated Country Strategy Mission Objective 1.1 - Improve socio-economic development..
